        <link id="build-style-article" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="/products/rsna/releasedAssets/css/build-article-8932601a697666afa607.css"/><article xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml" data-design="pill" data-has="right-rail" data-type="research-article" vocab="http://schema.org/" typeof="ScholarlyArticle" lang="en" dir="ltr"><header data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><div data-article-access="no" data-article-access-type="other" class="meta-panel"><div class="meta-panel__left-content"><div class="meta-panel__label"><span>Breast Imaging</span></div><div class="meta-panel__onlineDate">Feb 7 2020</div></div><div class="meta-panel__right-content"><div class="meta-panel__share"></div></div></div><h1 property="name"><i>BRCA</i> and Beyond: Comprehensive Image-rich Review of Hereditary Breast and Gynecologic Cancer Syndromes</h1><div class="contributors"><span class="authors"><span class="heading">Authors</span>: <span role="list"><span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con1"><span property="givenName">Stephanie Histed</span> <span property="familyName">Chung</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5821-1834" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-5821-1834</a> <a href="/cdn-cgi/l/email-protection#b2c1dad1dac7dcd5f2d0c5da9cdad3c0c4d3c0d69cd7d6c7" property="email" aria-label="Email address"><span class="__cf_email__" data-cfemail="86f5eee5eef3e8e1c6e4f1eea8eee7f4f0e7f4e2a8e3e2f3">[email&#160;protected]</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con2"><span property="givenName">Nina</span> <span property="familyName">Woldenberg</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con3"><span property="givenName">Antoinette R.</span> <span property="familyName">Roth</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con4"><span property="givenName">Rinat</span> <span property="familyName">Masamed</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con5"><span property="givenName">Wendy</span> <span property="familyName">Conlon</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MS</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9778-3712" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9778-3712</a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con6"><span property="givenName">Joshua G.</span> <span property="familyName">Cohen</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con7"><span property="givenName">Melissa M.</span> <span property="familyName">Joines</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a></span>, and <span property="author" typeof="Person" role="listitem"><a href="#con8"><span property="givenName">Maitraya K.</span> <span property="familyName">Patel</span>, <span property="honorificSuffix">MD</span></a> <a class="orcid-id" href="https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3329-3615" property="identifier" aria-label="ORCID identifier" target="_blank">https://orcid.org/0000-0003-3329-3615</a></span></span></span><a href="#tab-contributors" class="to-authors-affiliations" data-id="article-authors-viewall">Authors Info &amp; Affiliations</a></div><div class="core-self-citation"><div property="isPartOf" typeof="Periodical"><span class="heading">Publication</span>: <span property="name">RadioGraphics</span></div><div class="core-enumeration"><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationVolume">Volume <span property="volumeNumber">40</span></span><span class="delimiter">, </span><span property="isPartOf" typeof="PublicationIssue">Number <span property="issueNumber">2</span></span></div><div class="doi"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020190084" property="sameAs">https://doi.org/10.1148/rg.2020190084</a></div></div><div class="info-panel"><div class="info-panel__left-content"><div class="info-panel__metrics info-panel__item"></div></div><div class="info-panel__right-content"><div class="info-panel__article_tools info-panel__item">



        
        <div class="article-tools"><a href="/personalize/addFavoritePublication?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084" target="_blank" class="article-tools__favorite btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Add to favorites"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-add-favorite"></i><span class="sr-only">Add to favorites</span></a><a href="/action/addCitationAlert?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084" target="_blank" class="article-tools__citation btn btn--slim btn--inverse" data-toggle="tooltip" data-trigger="hover" data-original-title="Track Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-alert-bell"></i><span class="sr-only">Track Citations</span></a></div>
</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">In addition to the well-characterized <i>BRCA1</i> and <i>BRCA2</i> hereditary breast and ovarian cancer syndromes, many other syndromes that are associated with genetic mutations predispose individuals to an increased risk of breast and gynecologic malignancies. Many mutated genes encode for tumor-suppressor products and are inherited in an autosomal dominant manner. Mutations markedly increase an individual’s lifetime risk of cancers in different organ systems, depending on the associated syndrome. These syndromes include Lynch syndrome, the most common hereditary cause of endometrial cancer, and Peutz-Jeghers syndrome, which increases the risks of breast cancer, ovarian cancer, and cervical adenoma malignum. Li-Fraumeni syndrome and Cowden syndrome increase the risk of breast cancer, and Gorlin syndrome increases the risk of ovarian fibromas. With advances in genetic testing, clinicians’ knowledge and awareness of the numerous additional genes associated with breast and ovarian cancers, such as <i>ATM, CHEK2,</i> and <i>PALB2,</i> are rapidly expanding. Radiologists have essential roles in patient management, which include developing optimal screening protocols for these patients and closely monitoring them for the development or recurrence of disease-specific malignancies. Radiologists’ roles continue to increase and evolve as more mutations are identified and high-risk imaging screening recommendations expand to identify these patients. Understanding the epidemiologic, genetic, and pathophysiologic features and the cancers associated with these syndromes enables radiologists to appropriately contribute to patient management, ensure accurate and timely diagnosis, and make syndrome-specific imaging recommendations.</div><div role="paragraph"><sup>©</sup>RSNA, 2020</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190084">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190084">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig1.jpeg" height="1031" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Rectal adenocarcinoma in a 44-year-old woman with Lynch syndrome associated with deleterious gene mutation and a history of primary uterine adenocarcinoma and ovarian müllerian adenocarcinoma. The patient presented with abdominal pain and bloody stool. Coronal contrast material–enhanced CT image shows rectal adenocarcinoma (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig2.jpeg" height="1134" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span>. Endometrial carcinoma in a 45-year-old woman with an extensive family history of colorectal carcinoma and genetic test results that were positive for a pathologic MMR gene mutation compatible with Lynch syndrome. Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense mass (arrow) along the anterior lower uterine segment, cervix, and endocervical canal. Histopathologic analysis results were consistent with endometrial carcinoma of the nonendometrioid clear cell subtype.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig3a.jpeg" height="1219" width="1569" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Endometrial carcinoma in a 50-year-old woman who had an extensive family history of cancer and was found to have rectal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced staging CT image of the pelvis shows abnormal thickening of the endometrium (*). <b>(b)</b> Longitudinal transvaginal gray-scale US image shows a thickened endometrium (calipers). Histopathologic analysis revealed that the colon and endometrial tumors were morphologically and immunohistochemically distinct, with the endometrial tumors representing FIGO (International Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics) stage IA endometrial carcinoma. Genetic testing revealed heterozygosity for p.Q5242P mutation in the <i>MLH1</i> gene, consistent with Lynch syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig3b.jpeg" height="1219" width="1583" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Endometrial carcinoma in a 50-year-old woman who had an extensive family history of cancer and was found to have rectal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced staging CT image of the pelvis shows abnormal thickening of the endometrium (*). <b>(b)</b> Longitudinal transvaginal gray-scale US image shows a thickened endometrium (calipers). Histopathologic analysis revealed that the colon and endometrial tumors were morphologically and immunohistochemically distinct, with the endometrial tumors representing FIGO (International Federation of Gynecology and Obstetrics) stage IA endometrial carcinoma. Genetic testing revealed heterozygosity for p.Q5242P mutation in the <i>MLH1</i> gene, consistent with Lynch syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig4a.jpeg" height="1182" width="1370" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Ovarian carcinoma in a 45-year-old woman with pelvic pain and elevated cancer antigen 125 levels. <b>(a)</b> Transverse transvaginal gray-scale US image shows a 7-cm right adnexal mass (calipers) with low-level internal echoes and a septum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense adnexal mass (*), with additional adjacent hyperintense lesions (not shown) that correlated with the septated cystic areas seen at US. No enhancement was seen on contrast-enhanced MR images (not shown). The frozen pathologic specimen (not shown) was consistent with ovarian carcinoma, and the patient was found to have pathogenic mutations in <i>MSH2,</i> consistent with Lynch syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig4b.jpeg" height="1184" width="1783" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Ovarian carcinoma in a 45-year-old woman with pelvic pain and elevated cancer antigen 125 levels. <b>(a)</b> Transverse transvaginal gray-scale US image shows a 7-cm right adnexal mass (calipers) with low-level internal echoes and a septum (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense adnexal mass (*), with additional adjacent hyperintense lesions (not shown) that correlated with the septated cystic areas seen at US. No enhancement was seen on contrast-enhanced MR images (not shown). The frozen pathologic specimen (not shown) was consistent with ovarian carcinoma, and the patient was found to have pathogenic mutations in <i>MSH2,</i> consistent with Lynch syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig5a.jpeg" height="1428" width="1119" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in an 89-year-old woman with known Lynch syndrome and a history of recurrent colon carcinoma, endometrial carcinoma, and prior left-breast carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal diagnostic right-breast mammogram in a tomosynthesis spot compression view shows a suspicious irregular mass (circle). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding longitudinal gray-scale US image shows a suspicious irregular hypoechoic mass with angular margins and posterior acoustic shadowing (calipers). The histopathologic findings were consistent with poorly differentiated IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig5b.jpeg" height="1428" width="1818" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Invasive ductal carcinoma (IDC) in an 89-year-old woman with known Lynch syndrome and a history of recurrent colon carcinoma, endometrial carcinoma, and prior left-breast carcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Craniocaudal diagnostic right-breast mammogram in a tomosynthesis spot compression view shows a suspicious irregular mass (circle). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding longitudinal gray-scale US image shows a suspicious irregular hypoechoic mass with angular margins and posterior acoustic shadowing (calipers). The histopathologic findings were consistent with poorly differentiated IDC.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig6a.jpeg" height="1213" width="1795" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Ovarian carcinoma in a 43-year-old woman who had a strong family history of cancer and presented with bloating and constipation that had existed for several months. Clinical examination revealed a palpable abdominal mass. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal transabdominal gray-scale US image of the pelvis shows a 16.1-cm pelvic mass (calipers). <b>(b)</b> Coronal fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a bilobular partially cystic enhancing mass (arrows) and free fluid in the pelvis (*). Histopathologic findings were consistent with right ovarian mixed-type epithelioid carcinoma. Subsequent genetic testing revealed a p.A636P mutation in the <i>MSH2</i> gene, compatible with Lynch syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig6b.jpeg" height="1213" width="1354" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Ovarian carcinoma in a 43-year-old woman who had a strong family history of cancer and presented with bloating and constipation that had existed for several months. Clinical examination revealed a palpable abdominal mass. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal transabdominal gray-scale US image of the pelvis shows a 16.1-cm pelvic mass (calipers). <b>(b)</b> Coronal fat-suppressed T2-weighted MR image shows a bilobular partially cystic enhancing mass (arrows) and free fluid in the pelvis (*). Histopathologic findings were consistent with right ovarian mixed-type epithelioid carcinoma. Subsequent genetic testing revealed a p.A636P mutation in the <i>MSH2</i> gene, compatible with Lynch syndrome.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig7a.jpeg" height="1181" width="1318" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Adenoma malignum in a 47-year-old Ashkenazi Jewish woman with PJS who presented with abdominal and pelvic pain. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a low-attenuation mass (arrow) in the cervix, with endometrial cavity distention (*). Biopsies yielded squamous mucosa with invasive adenocarcinoma, compatible with adenoma malignum. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image through the pelvis after neoadjuvant chemoradiation shows rectal involvement (arrow) compatible with stage IVa disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig7b.jpeg" height="1181" width="1832" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Adenoma malignum in a 47-year-old Ashkenazi Jewish woman with PJS who presented with abdominal and pelvic pain. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced CT image shows a low-attenuation mass (arrow) in the cervix, with endometrial cavity distention (*). Biopsies yielded squamous mucosa with invasive adenocarcinoma, compatible with adenoma malignum. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted MR image through the pelvis after neoadjuvant chemoradiation shows rectal involvement (arrow) compatible with stage IVa disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig8a.jpeg" height="1142" width="1238" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. PJS in a 27-year-old woman with abnormal hair growth, hyperandrogenemia, and elevated human chorionic gonadotropin and α-fetoprotein levels. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique T2-weighted MR image shows a hypointense right adnexal mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows mild contrast enhancement (arrow). Unilateral salpingo-oophorectomy was converted to bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy owing to bilateral masses seen at diagnostic laparoscopy. Final histopathologic findings were consistent with right mixed germ-cell sex-cord stromal tumor and left dysgerminoma. Genetic testing revealed a pathologic <i>STK11</i> mutation consistent with PJS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig8b.jpeg" height="1142" width="1411" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. PJS in a 27-year-old woman with abnormal hair growth, hyperandrogenemia, and elevated human chorionic gonadotropin and α-fetoprotein levels. <b>(a)</b> Axial oblique T2-weighted MR image shows a hypointense right adnexal mass (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows mild contrast enhancement (arrow). Unilateral salpingo-oophorectomy was converted to bilateral salpingo-oophorectomy owing to bilateral masses seen at diagnostic laparoscopy. Final histopathologic findings were consistent with right mixed germ-cell sex-cord stromal tumor and left dysgerminoma. Genetic testing revealed a pathologic <i>STK11</i> mutation consistent with PJS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig9a.jpeg" height="1280" width="1196" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Clinically diagnosed PJS in a 42-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous cystic structures (arrows) throughout the cervix. Histopathologic findings were consistent with adenoma malignum. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted abdominal MR image also shows main pancreatic duct dilatation and multifocal cystic lesions (arrows) consistent with an intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows jejunal intussusception (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig9b.jpeg" height="1169" width="1765" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Clinically diagnosed PJS in a 42-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous cystic structures (arrows) throughout the cervix. Histopathologic findings were consistent with adenoma malignum. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted abdominal MR image also shows main pancreatic duct dilatation and multifocal cystic lesions (arrows) consistent with an intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows jejunal intussusception (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig9c.jpeg" height="1168" width="1782" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Clinically diagnosed PJS in a 42-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal T2-weighted MR image shows heterogeneous cystic structures (arrows) throughout the cervix. Histopathologic findings were consistent with adenoma malignum. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted abdominal MR image also shows main pancreatic duct dilatation and multifocal cystic lesions (arrows) consistent with an intraductal papillary mucinous neoplasm. <b>(c)</b> Axial T2-weighted MR image shows jejunal intussusception (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig10a.jpeg" height="1127" width="1316" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. PJS in a 48-year-old woman. Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a septated right adnexal mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis of the ovarian mass revealed a seromucinous cystadenoma, and the final pathologic specimen (not shown) showed that both ovaries had sex-cord tumorlets with annular tubules. At consensus pathologic analysis, it was determined that the cystic cervical lesion (* in <b>a</b>) represented endocervical glandular mucinous proliferation over adenoma malignum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig10b.jpeg" height="1127" width="1332" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. PJS in a 48-year-old woman. Sagittal contrast-enhanced fat-suppressed T1-weighted <b>(a)</b> and axial T2-weighted <b>(b)</b> MR images show a septated right adnexal mass (arrow). Histopathologic analysis of the ovarian mass revealed a seromucinous cystadenoma, and the final pathologic specimen (not shown) showed that both ovaries had sex-cord tumorlets with annular tubules. At consensus pathologic analysis, it was determined that the cystic cervical lesion (* in <b>a</b>) represented endocervical glandular mucinous proliferation over adenoma malignum.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig11a.jpeg" height="1437" width="1215" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. LFS in a 28-year-old woman with a history of pelvic leiomyosarcoma and right humeral osteosarcoma who was diagnosed with bilateral IDC at age 24 years. The patient had undergone bilateral mastectomy and neoadjuvant chemotherapy. Four years after the initial diagnosis, a new palpable lump was discovered in her right breast. <b>(a)</b> Diagnostic spot mammogram with an exaggerated craniocaudal lateral view shows a suspicious 5-mm mass (circle) corresponding to the palpable finding, with correlating US findings (not shown). Biopsy revealed DCIS. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced breast MR image shows a small area of nonmass enhancement at the biopsy site (arrow). Right breast lumpectomy with wide excision revealed recurrent IDC and DCIS. Genetic testing revealed a pathologic <i>TP53</i> mutation consistent with LFS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig11b.jpeg" height="1437" width="1434" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. LFS in a 28-year-old woman with a history of pelvic leiomyosarcoma and right humeral osteosarcoma who was diagnosed with bilateral IDC at age 24 years. The patient had undergone bilateral mastectomy and neoadjuvant chemotherapy. Four years after the initial diagnosis, a new palpable lump was discovered in her right breast. <b>(a)</b> Diagnostic spot mammogram with an exaggerated craniocaudal lateral view shows a suspicious 5-mm mass (circle) corresponding to the palpable finding, with correlating US findings (not shown). Biopsy revealed DCIS. <b>(b)</b> Contrast-enhanced breast MR image shows a small area of nonmass enhancement at the biopsy site (arrow). Right breast lumpectomy with wide excision revealed recurrent IDC and DCIS. Genetic testing revealed a pathologic <i>TP53</i> mutation consistent with LFS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig12a.jpeg" height="1455" width="1424" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span>. Breast cancer in a 52-year-old woman with a known <i>TP53</i> mutation who underwent high-risk breast cancer screening. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image of the left breast shows suspicious focal nonmass enhancement (arrow) at posterior depth. <b>(b)</b> Subsequently obtained diagnostic left breast lateromedial magnification mammogram shows suspicious grouped pleomorphic calcifications (circle) measuring 24 mm in the left upper outer quadrant, in the area of the MRI-depicted abnormality. The histopathologic specimen obtained at biopsy was consistent with microinvasive ductal carcinoma in a background of extensive high-nuclear-grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig12b.jpeg" height="1454" width="1228" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span>. Breast cancer in a 52-year-old woman with a known <i>TP53</i> mutation who underwent high-risk breast cancer screening. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted subtraction MR image of the left breast shows suspicious focal nonmass enhancement (arrow) at posterior depth. <b>(b)</b> Subsequently obtained diagnostic left breast lateromedial magnification mammogram shows suspicious grouped pleomorphic calcifications (circle) measuring 24 mm in the left upper outer quadrant, in the area of the MRI-depicted abnormality. The histopathologic specimen obtained at biopsy was consistent with microinvasive ductal carcinoma in a background of extensive high-nuclear-grade DCIS.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig13a.jpeg" height="1719" width="1073" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. LFS in a 13-year-old girl who presented with left-knee swelling. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows a metadiaphyseal lesion (arrow) with central enhancement in the distal left femur. Biopsy revealed telangiectatic osteosarcoma. Genetic testing revealed a pathologic <i>TP53</i> mutation consistent with LFS. <b>(b)</b> Axial fluid-attenuated inversion-recovery surveillance brain MR image shows a cortically based hyperintense right inferior parietal lobe lesion (arrow) that was nonenhancing at contrast-enhanced MRI (not shown), consistent with dysembryoplastic neuroepithelial tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig13b.jpeg" height="1719" width="1277" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. LFS in a 13-year-old girl who presented with left-knee swelling. <b>(a)</b> Coronal contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows a metadiaphyseal lesion (arrow) with central enhancement in the distal left femur. Biopsy revealed telangiectatic osteosarcoma. Genetic testing revealed a pathologic <i>TP53</i> mutation consistent with LFS. <b>(b)</b> Axial fluid-attenuated inversion-recovery surveillance brain MR image shows a cortically based hyperintense right inferior parietal lobe lesion (arrow) that was nonenhancing at contrast-enhanced MRI (not shown), consistent with dysembryoplastic neuroepithelial tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig14.jpeg" height="1128" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig14" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span>. Ovarian fibroma in a 50-year-old woman who was diagnosed with Gorlin syndrome at age 8 years. Her medical history was remarkable for multiple basal cell carcinomas (&gt;40), odontogenic cysts, palmar pits, and congenital bifid rib, as well as a recent left adnexal mass. Axial contrast-enhanced CT image through the pelvis shows the mass (arrow) in the left adnexa. Left salpingo-oophorectomy revealed a benign ovarian fibroma.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig14">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig15a.jpeg" height="1337" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. IDC in a 29-year-old woman with a palpable left-breast abnormality of 2 months’ duration. <b>(a)</b> Antiradial gray-scale US image of the left breast at the area of the palpable abnormality shows a 2.9-cm irregular hypoechoic mass (calipers) at the left 9-o’clock position and a second 1.3-cm irregularly shaped mass (BI-RADS 5) at the left 6-o’clock position. Results of core-needle biopsy of both masses were consistent with poorly differentiated IDC. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted reformatted subtraction MR image shows the left 9-o’clock irregularly shaped enhancing mass (*) and suspicious clumped nonmass enhancement (arrows) extending 5.7 cm from the mass. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted volumetric interpolated breath-hold examination MR image shows a necrotic left internal mammary lymph node (arrow). The patient underwent genetic testing, which revealed a c.968delA pathologic mutation in the <i>PTEN</i> gene.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig15b.jpeg" height="1118" width="1248" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. IDC in a 29-year-old woman with a palpable left-breast abnormality of 2 months’ duration. <b>(a)</b> Antiradial gray-scale US image of the left breast at the area of the palpable abnormality shows a 2.9-cm irregular hypoechoic mass (calipers) at the left 9-o’clock position and a second 1.3-cm irregularly shaped mass (BI-RADS 5) at the left 6-o’clock position. Results of core-needle biopsy of both masses were consistent with poorly differentiated IDC. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted reformatted subtraction MR image shows the left 9-o’clock irregularly shaped enhancing mass (*) and suspicious clumped nonmass enhancement (arrows) extending 5.7 cm from the mass. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted volumetric interpolated breath-hold examination MR image shows a necrotic left internal mammary lymph node (arrow). The patient underwent genetic testing, which revealed a c.968delA pathologic mutation in the <i>PTEN</i> gene.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig15c.jpeg" height="1118" width="1904" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. IDC in a 29-year-old woman with a palpable left-breast abnormality of 2 months’ duration. <b>(a)</b> Antiradial gray-scale US image of the left breast at the area of the palpable abnormality shows a 2.9-cm irregular hypoechoic mass (calipers) at the left 9-o’clock position and a second 1.3-cm irregularly shaped mass (BI-RADS 5) at the left 6-o’clock position. Results of core-needle biopsy of both masses were consistent with poorly differentiated IDC. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal contrast-enhanced T1-weighted reformatted subtraction MR image shows the left 9-o’clock irregularly shaped enhancing mass (*) and suspicious clumped nonmass enhancement (arrows) extending 5.7 cm from the mass. <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted volumetric interpolated breath-hold examination MR image shows a necrotic left internal mammary lymph node (arrow). The patient underwent genetic testing, which revealed a c.968delA pathologic mutation in the <i>PTEN</i> gene.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig16a.jpeg" height="941" width="1576" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Recurrent disease after multiple chemotherapy regimens for documented metastases to the liver and pleura in a 67-year-old woman with a history of recurrent progressive endometrioid endometrial cancer, with known <i>FGFR2, PF3K,</i> and <i>PTEN</i> mutations. Axial contrast-enhanced CT <b>(a)</b> and attenuation-correction PET <b>(b)</b> images through the pelvis show a fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose–avid soft-tissue nodule (arrow) along the posterior left bladder wall, indicating recurrent disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig16b.jpeg" height="941" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Recurrent disease after multiple chemotherapy regimens for documented metastases to the liver and pleura in a 67-year-old woman with a history of recurrent progressive endometrioid endometrial cancer, with known <i>FGFR2, PF3K,</i> and <i>PTEN</i> mutations. Axial contrast-enhanced CT <b>(a)</b> and attenuation-correction PET <b>(b)</b> images through the pelvis show a fluorine 18 fluorodeoxyglucose–avid soft-tissue nodule (arrow) along the posterior left bladder wall, indicating recurrent disease.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig17a.jpeg" height="1132" width="981" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Findings after lumpectomy and radiation treatment performed 18 years earlier in a 53-year-old woman with a remote history of left-breast malignancy. <b>(a)</b> Magnified lateromedial two-dimensional mammogram at the 11-o’clock to 12-o’clock position shows architectural distortion (circle) of the right breast. <b>(b)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image demonstrates a 1.1-cm irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins (arrows); these findings correlate with those seen at mammography <b>(a)</b>. Biopsy revealed IDC, and genetic testing revealed a deleterious p.l157T mutation in <i>CHEK2. </i> <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed extent-of-disease breast MR image shows a right-breast mass (arrow) at the 11-o’clock position and additional linear nonmass enhancement (arrowhead) at the 10-o’clock position, 7.5 cm posterior to the nipple. MRI-guided core-needle biopsy revealed invasive lobular carcinoma. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed breast MR image shows a third area of clumped NME (arrow) in the right lateral retroareolar region; this area also yielded invasive lobular carcinoma at final histopathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig17b.jpeg" height="1132" width="1402" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Findings after lumpectomy and radiation treatment performed 18 years earlier in a 53-year-old woman with a remote history of left-breast malignancy. <b>(a)</b> Magnified lateromedial two-dimensional mammogram at the 11-o’clock to 12-o’clock position shows architectural distortion (circle) of the right breast. <b>(b)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image demonstrates a 1.1-cm irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins (arrows); these findings correlate with those seen at mammography <b>(a)</b>. Biopsy revealed IDC, and genetic testing revealed a deleterious p.l157T mutation in <i>CHEK2. </i> <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed extent-of-disease breast MR image shows a right-breast mass (arrow) at the 11-o’clock position and additional linear nonmass enhancement (arrowhead) at the 10-o’clock position, 7.5 cm posterior to the nipple. MRI-guided core-needle biopsy revealed invasive lobular carcinoma. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed breast MR image shows a third area of clumped NME (arrow) in the right lateral retroareolar region; this area also yielded invasive lobular carcinoma at final histopathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig17c.jpeg" height="1422" width="1793" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Findings after lumpectomy and radiation treatment performed 18 years earlier in a 53-year-old woman with a remote history of left-breast malignancy. <b>(a)</b> Magnified lateromedial two-dimensional mammogram at the 11-o’clock to 12-o’clock position shows architectural distortion (circle) of the right breast. <b>(b)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image demonstrates a 1.1-cm irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins (arrows); these findings correlate with those seen at mammography <b>(a)</b>. Biopsy revealed IDC, and genetic testing revealed a deleterious p.l157T mutation in <i>CHEK2. </i> <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed extent-of-disease breast MR image shows a right-breast mass (arrow) at the 11-o’clock position and additional linear nonmass enhancement (arrowhead) at the 10-o’clock position, 7.5 cm posterior to the nipple. MRI-guided core-needle biopsy revealed invasive lobular carcinoma. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed breast MR image shows a third area of clumped NME (arrow) in the right lateral retroareolar region; this area also yielded invasive lobular carcinoma at final histopathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig17d.jpeg" height="1417" width="1657" aria-labelledby="fig17d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17d</span>. Findings after lumpectomy and radiation treatment performed 18 years earlier in a 53-year-old woman with a remote history of left-breast malignancy. <b>(a)</b> Magnified lateromedial two-dimensional mammogram at the 11-o’clock to 12-o’clock position shows architectural distortion (circle) of the right breast. <b>(b)</b> Transverse gray-scale US image demonstrates a 1.1-cm irregular hypoechoic mass with spiculated margins (arrows); these findings correlate with those seen at mammography <b>(a)</b>. Biopsy revealed IDC, and genetic testing revealed a deleterious p.l157T mutation in <i>CHEK2. </i> <b>(c)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed extent-of-disease breast MR image shows a right-breast mass (arrow) at the 11-o’clock position and additional linear nonmass enhancement (arrowhead) at the 10-o’clock position, 7.5 cm posterior to the nipple. MRI-guided core-needle biopsy revealed invasive lobular carcinoma. <b>(d)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced T1-weighted fat-suppressed breast MR image shows a third area of clumped NME (arrow) in the right lateral retroareolar region; this area also yielded invasive lobular carcinoma at final histopathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig17d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig18a.jpeg" height="1334" width="1169" aria-labelledby="fig18a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18a</span>. IDC in a 33-year-old woman with a history of papillary thyroid cancer, who presented with a palpable lesion in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Magnified lateromedial mammographic view over the palpable area shows approximately 7 cm of segmental pleomorphic calcifications in the left lower inner quadrant (oval) extending to the palpable area of concern. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal gray-scale US image shows a 2.4-cm irregular mass. Biopsy revealed moderately differentiated IDC. Contrast-enhanced breast MR image (not shown) showed the biopsy-sampled irregular enhancing mass at the left 6-o’clock position and suspicious segmental nonmass enhancement extending 6 cm and corresponding to the suspicious calcifications seen at mammography <b>(a)</b>. Genetic testing revealed a c.1100del mutation in <i>CHEK2</i> and a c.09_510del mutation in <i>PALB2.</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig18a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig18b.jpeg" height="1334" width="1484" aria-labelledby="fig18b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18b</span>. IDC in a 33-year-old woman with a history of papillary thyroid cancer, who presented with a palpable lesion in the left breast. <b>(a)</b> Magnified lateromedial mammographic view over the palpable area shows approximately 7 cm of segmental pleomorphic calcifications in the left lower inner quadrant (oval) extending to the palpable area of concern. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal gray-scale US image shows a 2.4-cm irregular mass. Biopsy revealed moderately differentiated IDC. Contrast-enhanced breast MR image (not shown) showed the biopsy-sampled irregular enhancing mass at the left 6-o’clock position and suspicious segmental nonmass enhancement extending 6 cm and corresponding to the suspicious calcifications seen at mammography <b>(a)</b>. Genetic testing revealed a c.1100del mutation in <i>CHEK2</i> and a c.09_510del mutation in <i>PALB2.</i><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig18b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig19a.jpeg" height="1770" width="585" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. Findings in a 58-year-old man, a known carrier of <i>BRCA2</i> and <i>CHEK2</i> mutations, with a history of prostate cancer and recent punch biopsy of the right nipple for assessment of a superficial lesion and corresponding palpable breast lesion, which were found at biopsy to represent poorly differentiated breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Right craniocaudal digital breast tomosynthesis image shows a 1.7-cm irregularly shaped mass (arrow) in the retroareolar region, corresponding to the palpable abnormality indicated by the breast biopsy marker. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal gray-scale US image over the palpable area shows a 1.7-cm irregularly shaped hypoechoic mass (calipers) that corresponds to the mammographic finding in <b>a</b> and the malignancy proven at biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190084/asset/images/large/rg.2020190084.fig19b.jpeg" height="761" width="1267" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. Findings in a 58-year-old man, a known carrier of <i>BRCA2</i> and <i>CHEK2</i> mutations, with a history of prostate cancer and recent punch biopsy of the right nipple for assessment of a superficial lesion and corresponding palpable breast lesion, which were found at biopsy to represent poorly differentiated breast cancer. <b>(a)</b> Right craniocaudal digital breast tomosynthesis image shows a 1.7-cm irregularly shaped mass (arrow) in the retroareolar region, corresponding to the palpable abnormality indicated by the breast biopsy marker. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal gray-scale US image over the palpable area shows a 1.7-cm irregularly shaped hypoechoic mass (calipers) that corresponds to the mammographic finding in <b>a</b> and the malignancy proven at biopsy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190084&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div